The maximum value of 3rem is picked over the preferred size when the screen width reaches 1000px or wider (assuming the default browser root font size of 1rem = 16px).At your current screen width of 800px, the preferred size evaluates to 2.5rem (40px), meaning the maximum value hasn't been triggered yet.Step-by-Step BreakdownTo find exactly when the maximum cap takes over, you solve for when the preferred value equals the maximum value:\(4\text{vw}+0.5\text{rem}=3\text{rem}\)Subtract the rem offset:\(4\text{vw}=2.5\text{rem}\)Convert rem to pixels (assuming 1rem = 16px):\(2.5\times 16\text{px}=40\text{px}\)Solve for 100% viewport width (\(100\text{vw}\)):If \(4\text{vw} = 40\text{px}\), then \(1\text{vw} = 10\text{px}\).\(100\text{vw}=1000\text{px}\)What Happens at 800px Width?At your specific screen size of 800px, the CSS clamp() function chooses the preferred middle value because it falls safely within the boundaries:Minimum limit: 1.5rem (24px)Preferred calculation: \(4\% \text{ of } 800\text{px} \ (32\text{px}) + 0.5\text{rem} \ (8\text{px}) = 40\text{px}\) (2.5rem)Maximum limit: 3rem (48px)


